# String Manipulation Methods in Python

This repository provides an overview and examples of commonly used Python string methods: str.capitalize(), str.swapcase(), and str.find(). These methods are part of the Python str class and are essential for manipulating string data.

## Table of Contents
- [Installation](#installation)
- [Usage](#usage)
  - [str.capitalize()](#strcapitalize)
  - [str.swapcase()](#strswapcase)
  - [str.find()](#strfind)
- [Examples](#examples)
- [Contributing](#contributing)
- [License](#license)



## Usage

### str.capitalize()

- Description: Capitalizes the first character of the string and converts all other characters to lowercase.
- Syntax: string.capitalize()
- Returns: A new string with the first character in uppercase and the rest in lowercase.

### Example
`python
original_string = "hello world!"
capitalized_string = original_string.capitalize()
print(capitalized_string)  # Output: Hello world!
str.swapcase()
Description: Swaps the case of each character in the string (uppercase to lowercase and vice versa).
Syntax: string.swapcase()
Returns: A new string with the case of each character swapped.
Example
python


original_string = "Hello World!"
swapped_case_string = original_string.swapcase()
print(swapped_case_string)  # Output: hELLO wORLD!
str.find()
Description: Searches the string for a specified substring and returns the lowest index of the substring if found. Returns -1 if not found.
Syntax: string.find(substring)
Returns: The lowest index of the substring or -1 if the substring is not found.
Example
python


original_string = "Hello World!"
index = original_string.find("World")
print(index)  # Output: 6

# Example of not finding a substring
not_found_index = original_string.find("Python")
print(not_found_index)  # Output: -1
Examples
The code examples for each method are provided above for your reference. Feel free to run them in any Python environment.

